==English==

===Etymology===
{{OE.}} ''[[aqueinten]]'', ''[[acointen]]'', Old French ''[[acointier]]'', Late Latin ''[[adcognitare]]'', from Latin ''[[ad]]'' + ''[[cognitus]]'', past participle of ''[[cognoscere]]'' to know; ''[[con-]]'' + ''[[noscere]] to know. See [[quaint]], [[know]]

===Transitive Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To furnish or give experimental knowledge of; to make (one) to know; to make familiar; -- followed by with.
#:''Before a man can speak on any subject, it is necessary to be '''acquainted''' with it.''  -[[John Locke]]
#:''A man of sorrows and '''acquainted''' with grief.''  -''Isaiah 53:3''
# {{cattag|ditransitive}} To communicate notice to; to inform; to make cognizant; -- followed by with (formerly, also, by of), or by that, introducing the intelligence; as, to '''acquaint''' a friend with the particulars of an act.
#:'''''Acquaint''' her here of my son Paris' love.''  -[[Shakespeare]], ''Romeo and Juliet'', III-iv
#:''I must '''acquaint''' you that I have received New dated letters from Northumberland.''  -{{Shak.}}, ''Henry IV, Part II'', IV-i
# ''(Obsolete):'' To familiarize; to accustom. - [[Evelyn?]]

====Derived terms====
*To be acquainted with: to be possessed of personal knowledge of; to be cognizant of; to be more or less familiar with; to be on terms of social intercourse with. 

====Synonyms====
*to [[inform]]
*to [[apprise]]
*to [[communicate]]
*to [[advise]]

